\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P:\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\left\{ 0\right\} \to\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 be a smooth map, with 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\lambda x\right)=\lambda^{d}P\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Prove that the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P_{*} & :\mathbb{RP}^{n}\to\mathbb{RP}^{k}\\
 & \left[x\right]\mapsto\left[P\left(x\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is well defined and smooth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The projective space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{RP}^{n}$
\end_inset

 consists of an equivalence class of points defined by the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\lambda y$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\backslash\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Thus for an equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

, it can be equally represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\lambda x\right]$
\end_inset

.
 According the the function 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{*}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P_{*}\left(\left[\lambda x\right]\right) & =\left[\lambda^{d}P\left(x\right)\right]\\
 & =\left[\lambda^{d}y\right]\\
 & =\left[y\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{*}$
\end_inset

 maps an equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 to an equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

 regardless of the representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

; therefore, it is well defined.
 By definition of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{*}$
\end_inset

 it maps an equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 using the smooth function 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 to the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[P\left(x\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Since the equivalence class is represented using 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\backslash\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{*}$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
If 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}=\left\{ \left(x,y\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}|x^{2}+y^{2}=1\right\} $
\end_inset

, prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $TS^{1}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\left(-\epsilon,\epsilon\right):S^{1}$
\end_inset

 denote a smooth curve on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(0\right)=p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U,\varphi\right)$
\end_inset

 be a chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}=\varphi\circ\gamma$
\end_inset

 denote the smooth curve in local coordinates.
 The tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 is defined as the set of equivalence class of curves such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{1}^{'}\left(0\right)=\tilde{\gamma}_{2}^{'}\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 As stated in class, this is independent of the chart used, so we can define
 the equivalence class in any chart.
 The derivative of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\frac{d\tilde{\gamma}}{dt}\right|_{t=0}=\alpha\frac{\partial}{\partial x},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, all of the curves in the same equivalence class can be identified
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U,\varphi\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\gamma\right]$
\end_inset

 represent the equivalence class whose derivative at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U,\varphi\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\frac{\partial}{\partial x},
\]

\end_inset

we can then create a map 
\begin_inset Formula $f:T_{p}S^{1}\to\left\{ p\right\} \times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(p,\left[\gamma\right]\right)=\left(p,\alpha\right).
\]

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}S^{1}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ p\right\} \times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since the map is invertible and smooth in both directions.
 The tangent bundle is the disjoint union of the tangent spaces; therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $TS^{1}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

