\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth compact manifold (without boundary), of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $F:M\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 a smooth map.
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 cannot be a submersion, and it cannot be an immersion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a smooth compact manifold (without boundary) of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, it is not a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and it can be covered by a finite number of charts denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U_{i},\varphi_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We denote the differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dF=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(F\circ\varphi^{-1}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a submersion if 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall p\in M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dF$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 are of the same dimension, this requires that the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $dF=2$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is an immersion if 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall p\in M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dF$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 This also requires that the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $dF=2$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is smooth, it is continuous and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(M\right)$
\end_inset

 is compact which means it is closed and bounded.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\left(-\epsilon,\epsilon\right)\to M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth curve such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a curve that moves straight towards a boundary in 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(M\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\gamma}{dt}=\text{constant}$
\end_inset

 .
 Then there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left(-\epsilon,\epsilon\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dF\circ\gamma}{dt}=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ\gamma$
\end_inset

 must stay inside 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(M\right)$
\end_inset

.
 At this point 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

, the differential 
\begin_inset Formula $dF$
\end_inset

 is not rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

; therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 cannot be a submersion nor an immersion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold with Riemannian metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\left[a,b\right]\to M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth curve, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:\left[c,d\right]\to\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 a diffeomorphism.
 Prove that the length of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the same as the length of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\circ\tau:\left[c,d\right]\to M$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U,\varphi\right)$
\end_inset

 be a chart on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 be the local representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\tau}$
\end_inset

 be the local representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\circ\tau$
\end_inset

 defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\tau}=\tilde{\gamma}\circ\tau.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism, it is a differentiable and a homeomorphism.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a curve that only moves 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

forward
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell\left(\gamma\right)=\int_{a}^{b}g\left(\left.\frac{d\tilde{\gamma}}{dt}\right|_{t},\left.\frac{d\tilde{\gamma}}{dt}\right|_{t}\right)^{1/2}dt,
\]

\end_inset

and the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell\left(\gamma\circ\tau\right) & =\int_{c}^{d}g\left(\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\gamma}}{\partial x}\right|_{\tau\left(t\right)}\frac{d\tau}{dt},\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\gamma}}{\partial x}\right|_{\tau\left(t\right)}\frac{d\tau}{dt}\right)^{1/2}dt\\
 & =\int_{c}^{d}g\left(\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\gamma}}{\partial x}\right|_{\tau\left(t\right)},\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\gamma}}{\partial x}\right|_{\tau\left(t\right)}\right)^{1/2}\left|\frac{d\tau}{dt}\right|dt,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\tau}{dt}$
\end_inset

 is a scalar and we are able to pull it out of the inner product.
 Notice that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\left[c,d\right]$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.g\left(\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\gamma}}{\partial x}\right|_{\tau\left(t\right)},\left.\frac{\partial\tilde{\gamma}}{\partial x}\right|_{\tau\left(t\right)}\right)^{1/2}\right|_{t=\beta}=\left.g\left(\frac{d\tilde{\gamma}}{dt},\frac{d\tilde{\gamma}}{dt}\right)^{1/2}\right|_{t=\tau\left(\beta\right)},
\]

\end_inset

which represents the height of the function that is being integrated and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\frac{d\tau}{dt}\right|$
\end_inset

 is the change of the infinitesimal width of the integral.
 This is similar to the change of basis where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\frac{d\tau}{dt}\right|$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian acting as the change in volume.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell\left(\gamma\right)=\ell\left(\gamma\circ\tau\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifold of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(U_{\lambda},\varphi_{\lambda}\right)\right\} _{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of coordinate charts which cover 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i,j}^{\lambda}:U_{\lambda}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i,j\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 State a set of necessary and sufficient conditions on the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ g_{i,j}^{\lambda}\right\} $
\end_inset

 so that there exists a Riemannian metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 whose coordinate description under the chart 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U_{\lambda},\varphi_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ g_{i,j}^{\lambda}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Riemannian metric is an assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of an inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(p\right)=\left\langle ,\right\rangle _{p}$
\end_inset

 on each tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 such that for any coordinate chart 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U,\varphi\right)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i,j}\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i,j\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 An inner product is symmetric, bi-linear, and positive definite.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 which can be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $v=v_{i}\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w=w_{i}\frac{\partial}{\partial x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 in local coordinates.
 We define the metric 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g^{\lambda}\left(v,w\right)=\sum_{i,j}g_{ij}^{\lambda}v_{i}w_{j}
\]

\end_inset

which we can represent in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g^{\lambda}\left(v,w\right)=\left[w_{1},\ldots,w_{n}\right]\begin{bmatrix}g_{11}^{\lambda} & \cdots & g_{1n}^{\lambda}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
g_{n1}^{\lambda} & \cdots & g_{nn}^{\lambda}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}v_{1}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

and we will denote as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[g_{ij}^{\lambda}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 By this definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[g_{ij}^{\lambda}\right]$
\end_inset

 is bilinear.
 We then impose the conditions that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}^{\lambda}=g_{ji}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[g_{ij}^{\lambda}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a positive definite matrix.
 Lastly, we need the metric to be independent of coordinate chart.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U_{1},\varphi_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(U_{2},\varphi_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 be coordinate charts on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 We can express the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 in either chart, and we want the measure of their length and angle to be
 independent of the chart we use.
 In other words, we want 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g^{1}\left(v,w\right)=g^{2}\left(v,w\right)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

.
 We can show this relation in matrix notation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[w_{1}^{1},\ldots,w_{n}^{1}\right]\begin{bmatrix}g_{11}^{1} & \cdots & g_{1n}^{1}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
g_{n1}^{1} & \cdots & g_{nn}^{1}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}v_{1}^{1}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}^{1}
\end{bmatrix}=\left[w_{1}^{2},\ldots,w_{n}^{2}\right]\begin{bmatrix}g_{11}^{2} & \cdots & g_{1n}^{2}\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
g_{n1}^{2} & \cdots & g_{nn}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}v_{1}^{2}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where the superscripts are used to denote the chart they are expressed in.
 Using the differential 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(\varphi_{2}\circ\varphi_{1}^{-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 we can map the vectors from the first chart to the second chart and map
 them back such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g^{1}\left(d\left(\varphi_{2}\circ\varphi_{1}^{-1}\right)^{-1}d\left(\varphi_{2}\circ\varphi_{1}^{-1}\right)v^{1},d\left(\varphi_{2}\circ\varphi_{1}^{-1}\right)^{-1}d\left(\varphi_{2}\circ\varphi_{1}^{-1}\right)v^{2}\right)=g^{1}\left(v,w\right).
\]

\end_inset

Using this relation we get the last condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(d\left(\varphi_{2}\circ\varphi_{1}^{-1}\right)^{-1}\right)^{\top}\left[g_{ij}^{1}\right]d\left(\varphi_{2}\circ\varphi_{1}^{-1}\right)^{-1}=\left[g_{ij}^{2}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

